title: For Sale:  .308 Sniper/Target Rifle
postcontent: For sale is my DPMS GII Bull model .308 with just about everything a shooter needs to get started in target/long-range shooting. The rifle was purchased brand new when the GII first came out in 2014; the serial number starts off with "AA00". It has only 150 rounds through it following the DPMS recommended barrel break-in procedure. It is sub-mil accurate, and with a practiced shooter, can do even better. My best 5-shot group was a 0.82" at 100 yards. The rifle comes with the following features and accessories:-Stock free-floating stainless steel 24" long 1" diameter bull barrel, 1:9 twist rate-Stock black canvas adjustable sling-Stock A2 buttstock with custom hand-stitched coyote tan wrap/cheekrest (wrap has inserts inside on top of the buttstock to get the proper cheek height for me)-Stock free-float aluminum front handguard with custom hnad-stitched coyote tan wrap (wrap insulates the aluminum handguard from the cold)-Ergo Tactical Deluxe pistol grip with palm shelf-Harris 9-13" swivel bipod with notched legs (model HBLMS)-AADMOUNT 30mm diameter 20MOA scope mount-SWFA SS 3-15X42 FFP mildot reticle with 1/10th mil turrets-SWFA flip-up Scope Caps-1x stock steel 20 round magazine-5x Magpul Gen M3 10-round magazines with covers-Hand-stiched coyote tan heavy duty rear shooting bag-Heavy duty olive green drag bag-50 rounds of Hornady 178-grain A-Max mild reload with a muzzle velocity of about 2700fps-Various other accessories including lens pen, bore snake, star hex key for scope mount, spare canvas and paracordSome other things to note: all functions, ergonomics, and takedown are the same as any AR-style rifle. This made it very easy for me to learn, and is a comfortable shooter from prone or bench. Recoil is very mild for a .308, thanks to the AR-style gas design and relatively hefty weight. This rifle is not exactly light at about 14 pounds unloaded.I broke the barrel in using 100 rounds of cheap white-box winchester .308 147-grain with zero failures of anykind. Of course, the twist rate in the barrel favors a heavier bullet, so it is highly recommended to use a 165 to 180 grain bullet for normal shooting. I personally prefer the ballistics of the 178 AMAX, which is what the rifle is zeroed in for.I paid well over $2500 for everything, and am asking $2200. I just don't have time to shoot anymore since I moved to Georgia and started my new job.
